The paper deals with geometric graphs and matching problems, which are typical topics in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of graphs and combinatorial techniques to study the properties of the geometric objects suggests that the paper could also fit in the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) category. The study of structural properties of graphs and the analysis of bounds on their size and complexity are also relevant to the algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) category. The investigation of the block cut point graph of a geometric graph and the derivation of bounds on the number of edges of a certain type of graph suggest that the paper could also belong to the graph theory (cs.GT) category. Finally, the use of equivalence results between different types of geometric graphs and the analysis of their properties could also fit in the social and information networks (cs.SI) category.
